{"title_page": "Esztergom Synagogue", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n{{Short description|Synagogue in Hungary}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Historic building\n| image = Esztergom.Synagogue.jpg\n| caption =\n| name = Esztergom Synagogue\n| location_town = [[Esztergom]]\n| location_country = [[Hungary]]\n| architect =\n| client =\n| engineer =\n| construction_start_date = 1859\n| completion_date = 1888\n| date_demolished =\n| cost =\n| structural_system =\n| style =\n}}\n\nThe '''Esztergom Synagogue''' is the oldest Jewish synagogue located in [[Esztergom]], [[Hungary]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bratislavaadventure.com/en/travelguide/what-to-see/moorish-synagogue-esztergom.html|title=Bratislava Adventure|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The synagogue was established in 1859 and completed in 1888.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/esztergom|title=Beit Hatfutsot|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The majority of the congregation was deported during the Holocaust.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.funiq.hu/2390-synagogue-esztergom|title=funiQ|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe synagogue was damaged during World War II. After a long renovation, it was awarded by ATNSA (Association of Technical and Natural Science Associations) in Esztergom  in 1980 and renamed as ''House of Technology''. In 2006, it served as a conference venue for the municipality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://budapestbeacon.com/jobbik-books-synagogue-for-valentines-day-political-rally/|title=Jobbik books synagogue for Valentine's day political rally|last=Kov\u00e1cs|first=-Zolt\u00e1n|date=2014-01-30|website=The Budapest Beacon|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nEsztergom has been home for large number of Jewish communities since the [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d dynasty]]. There are references to a synagogue in Esztergom dating back to as early as 1050.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Patai|first=Raphael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LLuPS1yVDf8C&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=Esztergom+1050+year+synagogue&source=bl&ots=yDFE5i4J0h&sig=ACfU3U35PE7HquvF-8XZKqyrw-48C4YI6g&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj_m9H9gNXoAhUEHc0KHdpBDlgQ6AEwFHoECAsQLA#v=onepage&q=Esztergom%201050%20year%20synagogue&f=false|title=The Jews of Hungary: History, Culture, Psychology|date=1996|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=978-0-8143-2561-2|language=en}}</ref> This is evidenced by the fact that two Jewish merchants from Regensburg, who came to the city from Russia, met their comrades in front of the synagogue.\n\nAfter the reformation, Esztergom welcomed Jewish merchants, who built a synagogue for themselves. In 1858, another synagogue was erected on the site of today's synagogue in the former village of Szenttam\u00e1s.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAbout thirty years later, architect [[\u00d6d\u00f6n Lechner]] and [[Lip\u00f3t Baumhorn]], was commissioned to design a new synagogue. This was Baumhorn's first solo work. The synagogue was designed in the style of Late-romantic period, originally single-story with a gallery for the women of the congregation. It was inaugurated in 1888 by [[Ign\u00e1c Weisz]], rabbi of [[Immanuel L\u00f6w|Imm\u00e1nuel L\u0151w]] and [[Szeged]].<ref>{{https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/esztergom|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\nUntil World War II, it was frequented by the Jews of Esztergom and the surrounding villages. During World War II, the synagogue was bombed and got badly damaged. Most of the Jews \u2014 about five hundred \u2014 were deported, and have not had a significant community in the city ever since. Since then, only the name Imah\u00e1z utca remains of the original part of the building. {{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe empty building was awarded in 1964 to the organization of ATNSA (Association of Technical and Natural Science Associations) in the city. This was when the first major renovations began. Space was partitioned with reinforced concrete slabs, breaking down the women's gallery. From 1980 to 1981, it housed the Tech House, which until 2006 served as a conference center.\n\nOver the next few years, the organization has continually renovated and completely restructured to be able to hold conferences and lectures. It has created lecture rooms, interpreting booths, rooms suitable for receptions, and district heating has been introduced. In 1996, the roof and dome shells were renovated.\n\nAccordingly, several prestigious events took place between the walls of the former Jewish temple. Politicians often gave lectures here on their tours.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In 2006, the municipality bought the Technika House for 70 million HUF. After that, the office of the Ister-Granum Euroregion operated there for a short time, until in 2008 it moved to the building of the County Hall of Botty\u00e1n J\u00e1nos Street.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?rlz=1C1CHBD_enIN883IN883&q=county+hall+of+botty%C3%A1n+street&tbm=isch&source=univ&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjij9Lm4t7oAhUr8XMBHRfBD0oQsAR6BAgJEAE&biw=1366&bih=657|title=county hall of botty\u00e1n street - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nRecently, controversy has surrounded the Synagogue. In 2014, Hungary's neo-nazi political party book the Synagogue for a political rally.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kov\u00e1cs |first1=Zolt\u00e1n |title=Jobbik books synagogue for Valentine\u2019s day political rally |url=https://budapestbeacon.com/jobbik-books-synagogue-for-valentines-day-political-rally/ |website=Budapest Beacon |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> Citizens of Esztergom were enraged at the disrespect towards the Jewish community and asked the government to cancel the event.\n\n== Description ==\nThe two-story monument synagogue is 1216 square meters large and contains a two tower units that jet out from both sides of the fa\u00e7ade. These are connected by a triple-arched, arcade foyer. The original 1888 marble staircase leads to a conference room upstairs with interpreting booths.\n\nThe Martyr Monument in front of the building was made according to the plans of Istv\u00e1n Martsa. The original 2.5-meter bronze work was made for the monument competition in Mauthausen and was placed in the Hungarian barracks of the Auschwitz camp museum. Today's statue was erected in 1985. Its pedestal is a bonfire made of railway sleepers. A plaque commemorates the abductees on the wall of the building.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Myers|first=Richard S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N3zM1injK8QC&pg=PA216&lpg=PA216&dq=the+Martyr+Monument+hungary+esztergom&source=bl&ots=dKkSf7AhQf&sig=ACfU3U0upkn_0HdwDqXRCigWadwt0STgDA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtx-iHpNzoAhVQIKwKHf5bDDwQ6AEwDXoECAwQKA#v=onepage&q=the%20Martyr%20Monument%20hungary%20esztergom&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Catholic Social Thought, Social Science, and Social Policy: Supplement|last2=Varacalli|first2=Joseph A.|date=2007|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8266-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://epiteszforum.hu/node/12112 \u00c9p\u00edt\u00e9szf\u00f3rum - Az esztergomi zsinag\u00f3ga \u00fajj\u00e1\u00e9led\u00e9se]\n* Pifk\u00f3 P\u00e9ter \u2013 Zachar Anna:Esztergom helyt\u00f6rt\u00e9neti kronol\u00f3gi\u00e1ja a kezdetekt\u0151l 1950-ig\n* Kom\u00e1rom-Esztergom megye m\u0171eml\u00e9kjegyz\u00e9ke (2006)\n* Esztergom 2000 enciklop\u00e9dia\n* Annales Strigonienses 1994, 145. o.\n* [https://budapestbeacon.com/jobbik-books-synagogue-for-valentines-day-political-rally/ Budapest Beacon - Jobbik books synagogue for Valentine\u2019s day political rally]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:19th-century synagogues]]\n[[Category:Jewish Hungarian history]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Esztergom]]\n[[Category:Synagogues in Hungary]]\n", "